A hands-on intro to if statements, random numbers, and the Math class using a Mad Libs game and a shopping cart program
Nobody tells you this, but the fastest way to actually learn a programming language is to build something dumb with it. Not a “todo list app,” not a “calculator,” something genuinely silly. Which is how I ended up building a Mad Libs generator in Java and realized, halfway through, that I’d accidentally used arithmetic, conditionals, random numbers, and the Math class without even trying.
So let’s build it together. By the end you’ll have a working Mad Libs game and, more importantly, you’ll actually understand why each piece works instead of just copy-pasting it and hoping.
Step 1: Arithmetic — Because Even Silly Games Need Math
Java handles math the way you’d expect, but with a couple of gotchas that trip up literally everyone at least once.
int a = 10;
int b = 3;System.out.println(a + b); // 13
System.out.println(a - b); // 7
System.out.println(a * b); // 30
System.out.println(a / b); // 3 <- wait what
System.out.println(a % b); // 1
That a / b giving you 3 instead of 3.333... is not a bug, it's Java being extremely literal. When you divide two int values, Java assumes you want an int back, so it just chops off everything after the decimal. This is called integer division and it will get you eventually if nobody warns you.
The fix: make at least one of the numbers a double.
double result = (double) a / b;
System.out.println(result); // 3.3333333333333335That (double) in front is called a cast you're basically telling Java "trust me, treat this like a decimal number for this one operation."
And %? That's the modulo operator, and it gives you the remainder after division. It looks useless until you realize it's the secret behind checking if a number is even, cycling through a list, or spoiler generating random Mad Libs prompts.
Step 2: If Statements — Teaching Java to Make Decisions
An if statement is just Java asking "is this true or not?" and doing something different depending on the answer.
int age = 17;if (age >= 18) {
System.out.println("you can vote");
} else {
System.out.println("not yet, patience");
}
You can stack these with else if when there's more than two outcomes:
int score = 85;if (score >= 90) {
System.out.println("A - certified genius");
} else if (score >= 80) {
System.out.println("B - respectable");
} else if (score >= 70) {
System.out.println("C - it's giving mediocre");
} else {
System.out.println("bro we need to talk");
}
The comparisons you’ll use constantly: == (equal to), != (not equal), >, <, >=, <=. Quick warning that catches literally everyone at some point = sets a value, == compares two values. Use the wrong one and Java will either yell at you or silently do something you didn't mean, depending on the situation.
Step 3: Random Numbers — Adding Chaos on Purpose
Java’s Random class lets you generate numbers you don't control, which is exactly what makes games fun instead of predictable.
import java.util.Random;Random rand = new Random();
int diceRoll = rand.nextInt(6) + 1; // gives 1-6
System.out.println("you rolled a " + diceRoll);
Breaking that down: rand.nextInt(6) gives you a random number from 0 to 5. Adding + 1 shifts the range up to 1 through 6, because nobody's dice starts at zero.
This is exactly the trick you’d use to randomly pick a Mad Libs prompt, randomly select an item price in a shopping cart, or randomly decide anything you want to feel less scripted.
Step 4: The Math Class — Your Built-In Calculator on Steroids
Beyond basic arithmetic, Java ships with a whole Math class full of useful pre-built functions so you're not reinventing formulas from scratch.
System.out.println(Math.max(4, 9)); // 9
System.out.println(Math.min(4, 9)); // 4
System.out.println(Math.abs(-15)); // 15
System.out.println(Math.pow(2, 5)); // 32.0
System.out.println(Math.sqrt(64)); // 8.0
System.out.println(Math.round(4.6)); // 5You’ll reach for Math.max and Math.min constantly once you know they exist comparing scores, capping values, keeping a number inside a range. Math.round is clutch anytime you're dealing with money and don't want to show your user $19.999999997.
Now Let’s Actually Build the Mad Libs Game
Time to combine everything. The concept: ask the user for some words, plug them into a silly story template, and randomly pick which version of the story to tell.
import java.util.Scanner;
import java.util.Random;public class MadLibs {
public static void main(String[] args) {
Scanner input = new Scanner(System.in);
Random rand = new Random();
System.out.println("give me an adjective:");
String adjective = input.nextLine();
System.out.println("give me an animal:");
String animal = input.nextLine();
System.out.println("give me a number:");
int number = input.nextInt();
System.out.println("give me a verb (ending in -ing):");
input.nextLine(); // clears leftover newline from nextInt()
String verb = input.nextLine();
int chaosLevel = rand.nextInt(3) + 1;
System.out.println("\n--- your story ---");
if (chaosLevel == 1) {
System.out.println("once upon a time, a " + adjective + " " + animal +
" was " + verb + " through the city at 3am for no reason.");
} else if (chaosLevel == 2) {
System.out.println("scientists discovered " + number + " " + adjective +
" " + animal + "s " + verb + " in perfect formation. nobody knows why.");
} else {
System.out.println("breaking news: a " + adjective + " " + animal +
" has been " + verb + " nonstop for " + number + " hours straight.");
}
}
}
Every single concept we just covered shows up here: Scanner for input, String concatenation to build the story, Random to pick which version plays, and that little input.nextLine() cleanup trick to stop Scanner from glitching after nextInt().
Run it a few times same inputs, different random story each time. That’s the whole magic trick behind half of the “randomly generated” content on the internet, by the way. It’s just if statements and a Random object wearing a trench coat.
Bonus Round: The Shopping Cart Program
Since we’ve got arithmetic, if statements, and Math class fresh in the tank, let’s use them for something more “real world” a simple shopping cart that totals items and applies a discount if you spend enough.
import java.util.Scanner;public class ShoppingCart {
public static void main(String[] args) {
Scanner input = new Scanner(System.in);
System.out.println("how many items are you buying?");
int itemCount = input.nextInt();
double total = 0;
for (int i = 1; i <= itemCount; i++) {
System.out.println("price of item " + i + ":");
double price = input.nextDouble();
total += price;
}
System.out.println("\nsubtotal: $" + Math.round(total * 100.0) / 100.0);
if (total >= 100) {
double discount = total * 0.15;
total -= discount;
System.out.println("you unlocked a 15% discount, nice");
} else if (total >= 50) {
double discount = total * 0.05;
total -= discount;
System.out.println("you unlocked a 5% discount");
} else {
System.out.println("spend more to unlock a discount");
}
System.out.println("final total: $" + Math.round(total * 100.0) / 100.0);
}
}
Notice what’s doing the heavy lifting: a loop to collect each price, arithmetic to keep a running total, if/else if to decide the discount tier, and Math.round so you're not displaying a total like $87.34999999998 like some kind of monster.
Why This Combo Actually Matters
Mad Libs and a shopping cart look like completely different programs, but under the hood they’re built from the same five ingredients: arithmetic, conditionals, randomness, input, and a few Math class shortcuts. That’s the real unlock here: once these five things click, you’re not “learning Java” anymore in a vague sense; you’re actually building things with it.
Every app that has ever calculated a discount, rolled a die, quizzed you, or randomized your daily horoscope runs on the same logic, just with better graphics wrapped around it.
So go build something dumb. Genuinely, the dumber the concept, the more you tend to learn, because you stop worrying about whether it’s “impressive” and focus on making it work.

If this got you to actually open your IDE instead of just reading about it, follow for more chaotic, hands-on Java breakdowns coming soon.
